{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514887"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:27:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:27:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12397"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.2,0.01,0.56,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41933"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4905"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26914"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"496"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44957"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41933"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a two-day history of earache, particularly during the night. Further history elicits that she has also been experiencing difficulty hearing and itchiness of the ear canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination of the ear reveals marked pinnal tenderness, crusty discharge and oedema of the external auditory canal. The tympanic membrane is unable to be visualised. Dry aural toilet is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Analgesia","Kenacomb otic ear drops (Triamcinolone acetonide, neomycin, gramicidin and nystatin)","Oral prednisolone","Ciproxin HC ear drops (Ciprofloxacin \u0026 hydrocortisone)","Sofradex ear drops (Framycetin sulfate and gramicidin)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is suffering from acute otitis externa. The first step in management should always be aural toilet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the tympanic membrane is unable to visualised, \u003Cstrong\u003Ekenacomb otic\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esofradex ear drops \u003C/strong\u003Eshould not be used. These both contain aminoglycoside antibiotics. Aminoglycosides should be avoided if the tympanic membrane cannot be visualised, as they can cause ototoxicity if there is a perforation of the membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiproxin HC ear drops \u003C/strong\u003Eare a combination of ciprofloxacin (a fluoroquinolone) and hydrocortisone. Topical fluoroquinolones are the treatment of choice for otitis externa with a perforated tympanic membrane or where the membrane cannot be visualised, as they do not cause ototoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesia\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to control otalgia, but will not treat the underlying infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in the treatment of acute otitis externa if the canal is very swollen, as it will help reduce pain and swelling. In severe cases oral prednisolone can be used as second line treatment. Ciproxin HC ear drops contain a topical corticosteroid to aid in treating the inflammation associated with the condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aminoglycosides should be avoided in the treatment of otitis externa if the integrity of the tympanic membrane cannot be ascertained."],"references":["Kaushik V, Malik T, Saeed SR. Interventions for acute otitis externa. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. 2010(1).","Rosenfeld RM, Schwartz SR, Cannon CR, Roland PS, Simon GR, Kumar KA, et al. Clinical practice guideline: acute otitis externa. Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2014;150(1 Suppl):S1-s24."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26914"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12397"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26914"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-27T15:01:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-27T15:01:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4905"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41933"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings",